I owned a pair for 18 months before this purchase until a pit bull decided to use them as a chew toy. Soundwise they are wonderful but they do have a bit of a pronounced low mid range. If your ears aren't refined, these will likely be the best sounding headphones you've heard. The battery life is so long that it doesn't occur to me to charge them because it's so long between charges. Of course when they eventually die I have to lol. Oh, the noise canceling. The best, bar none unless there have been some new developments elsewhere. These are almost like being in a sound isolation booth. There is also the ability to fine tune them to be even more efficient at blocking your particular surroundings. I can't recommend these enough. The one bad thing. There is this really dumb touch control system on one headphone which requires super powers to work properly so I just don't use it but every once in a while it can be accidentally pressed and a song will get skipped which is really annoying. Other than that, love 'em.", 'It\'s hard to know where to begin actually. I\'ve owned several pairs of ANC headphones over the years and by and large, I\'ve been seriously underwhelmed. They all worked to some degree or another, but there was always SOMETHING about them that just didn\'t "work" for me. Not comfortable, the ANC was too weak. The audio quality was poor/terrible, etc. The honest truth is, people seem to believe that ANC is necessary under circumstances where they really aren\'t needed, and are under the false impression that it somehow makes the music sound better. That is simply untrue. All ANC does is allow you to concentrate better on the audio under circumstances where the ambient noise around you makes it difficult, such as on a plane flight. In truth, audio quality and ANC are separate things altogether.  These are the international version, and therefore, they came out of the box with Chinese being the language you hear whenever you turn them on/off. This is a simple correction via the app, so don\'t worry if you cannot understand anything at first. The app is in English, so give it a thorough runthru so you will know about what to expect. You may need an immediate firmware or software update. With the XM3\'s, via bluetooth, these updates can be excruciatingly LONG. Have patience, but DO keep that in mind. It can take 3045 minutes or possibly a little longer. Mine came with the latest update preloaded, and for that I was grateful.  Let\'s start with audio quality, since that is the #1 reason to buy a pair of headphones. As a Sony fan and a radio broadcaster with 30 years of experience, I can say without reservation that Sony makes some of the best allaround headphones you can buy, period. Some audiophiles may say different, but the honest truth is, audio quality is almost as much subjective as it is a fact for some. No audiophile listens to music with headphones on more than I have over the last 30 years, I can tell you that. But everyone is slightly different and your tastes may vary...this is important to remember. The XM3\'s sound phenomenal. Great bass, low\'s, mid\'s and highs were fairly crisp and punchy. It all fades a bit when the ANC is enabled however, so keep that in mind. You sacrifice a little audio for the noise cancellation on, so don\'t be shocked...but it isn\'t a lot. It still sounds great. It could be a bit louder perhaps, but that didn\'t bug me at all. I was particularly grateful that Sony includes a cord which you can use for listening to audio on a plane, or for me, to plug into my control board at my radio station (though I needed an adapter, which is standard for broadcasting, so I have several). Not all ANC headphones come with this option (Bose 700 for instance...)  ANC...wow. When they say Industry Leading, they aren\'t kidding. I was busy adjusting my app when a coworker came in and walked up to me and I didn\'t even hear them enter and ask me a question. When I suddenly registered I wasn\'t alone in my studio, I nearly jumped out of my skin. Holy friggin\' cow. That ANC WORKS! You can of course adjust it all via the app and by cupping your hand over the right earpiece and the audio almost immediately lowers and the ANC turns off and you can hear your surroundings. It\'s actually quite amazing how good this works. One thing I dislike about noise cancelling is how many experience a "pressure" on your ears when it turns on. This is something I have always just lived with, but was constantly annoyed by. The XM3\'s have all but eliminated this. It was turned on by default, so I hardly even recognized it until I found the function in the app. Well done Sony.  As for comfort, as someone who is fairly used to wearing headphones for literally hoursonend in my studio, I place a higher standard on comfort than perhaps many others. If I\'m going to wear something for this long each day, they certainly better be comfortable. What good is great audio quality if the comfort isn\'t there? You may not place comfort as high on the list of "must haves" when you buy headphones, but for me, it very well may be the most important factor, and one I forget to mention all too often. The XM3\'s are genuinely comfortable. Keep in mind everyone is different, so what is great for some may not be for all...but the premium build certainly helps. Not sure what the earcups are made of, soft leather, a fake simulation...? I dunno. But they sure are soft. Light YEARS better than the cheap one\'s Sony includes on their Professional Studio Monitors (MDR 7506). As with pretty much ANY overtheear headphones, the better the seal, the hotter they tend to be the warmer the outside temp happens to be. After prolonged wear, you may experience some ear sweat (I don\'t know any other way to put it). I find that if it\'s going to be that warm, I remove them often in between songs to help keep that issue to a minimum. But as for sheer comfort, Sony has nailed it here. I could wear these all day.  I briefly considered the XM4\'s, but for the added price, the advantages weren\'t significant enough for me to want to pay the extra. For my particular needs/wants, the XM3\'s are more than sufficient...plus, they are around $150 cheaper, and honestly, for this price, money talks. Having tried on a pair of the XM4\'s, I can say the ANC functionality seems no different to me. There ARE several other things they come with that the older model doesn\'t have, so keep that in mind, but audioquality wise, the difference is essentially nil. They both sound great.  The XM3\'s come with a carrying case! It seems that of all the expensive headphones I\'ve bought over the years, many either come with a pouch, or nothing at all and this is flatout bothersome...especially considering what some cost (Master & Dynamic, I\'m looking at YOU). Nice to have an included case that allows you to fold your cans up sufficiently so that the case doesn\'t take up much room wherever you plan to store/carry them. Nice touch, Sony. Yes, I\'ve seen better cases, but I\'ve also seen much, MUCH worse, so no issues in this dept as far as I\'m concerned.  I got the silver version, but I\'m not exactly sure how they came up with this description. Either someone at Sony is colorblind, or attempting to pull a joke on us because these are decidedly NOT silver. Sort of a light tan/brown color yes...but absolutely NOT silver. It\'s almost a joke they even chose to go with this as the color description. Seriously, what gives, Sony??  I do not use my XM3\'s for calling, so I cannot comment on call quality, but from everything I\'ve heard, this is one area where Sony could use some work.  Being able to pair multiple devices simultaneously isn\'t something I have ever had to do, so if I\'m being honest, it isn\'t an issue for me. With that said however, I am a little surprised it was not included. the Sony XM3 ANC earbuds have it (and they came out close to the same time as their bigger headphone counterparts), and it\'s been tech that has been around far longer than the headphones have, so I\'m a little mystified they did not make it a standard feature. Especially when you consider that Sony HAD to know a good number of their direct competitors would be including it and going after all the potential consumers who viewed this as a dealbreaker...but may have otherwise purchased a pair. Seriously, they have lost a literal mint by not including it, and that simply does not make sense to me.  I love how Sony included an adapter for plane flight to plug into in case you wish to watch video next time you fly across country. Several other (more expensive) models do not offer this as even an option, making the headphones useless for this specific purpose on flights. Many will be okay with this simply because they\'ll use theirs for watching content on their smartphones instead, but dang, it\'s nice to have as an option for either/or that the Bose 700 doesn\'t even offer. Could be a deal breaker for some.  Build quality can be subjective for some. The honest truth is, I take VERY GOOD care of my good headphones, and as a result, they last. My Professional Studio Monitors (the MDR 7506\'s I mentioned earlier) I have had for 8+ years and they not only look as good as they did when I bought them, but they still sound absolutely fantastic (I did however, replace the ear cushions, the ones that come standard are just plain crap on those models...I got some memory foam versions and they have been perfect). Take care of your cans and you will get many years worth of use out of them. For what they charge these days, it\'s important to treat them well if you wish to truly get the most out of them. I don\'t use mine for exercise (I don\' think they would stay in place well enough for any type of vigorous activity, but that goes for essentially any overtheear headphones that I\'m aware of) so I don\'t have to worry about that. But I fold mine up after each use and put them away carefully. I also have a headphone stand I hang them from while I\'m at work, so they get plenty of TLC. If you tend to be more harsh on your headphones, keep in mind the result will most certainly be a shorter lifespan, and for some that\'ll be upsetting, but like I said, take care of them, and they\'ll last...it\'s as simple as that.  I\'m sure I\'ll have updates, but so far, Sony knocked this one out of the park BIG time. Read more', "I also ordered a Bose Quiet Comfort 35 II limited edition. All Reviews: ['No soy un maestro de la audiofilia pero sin duda un gran porcentaje de la gente ha quedado maravillado con éste producto, excelentes audífonos y solo puedo decir dense la oportunidad de probar unos productos de ésta marca. Excelentes anker soundcore liberty 2 pro.', "As others have mentioned, the sound quality of these Liberty 2 Pro earbuds is excellent. So good, in fact, that quality here really comes down to personal preference, and that's different for everyone. But Anker even has that covered, and brilliantly. The app allows you to browse through a wide range of EQ curves offered by notable music producers. This covers the subjective opinion issue of sound quality, as you should be able to find a curve that meets your personal taste. If not, the HearID autoEQ does an impressive job of playing Dr. Audiologist by estimating your actual hearing and adjusting the EQ to compensate for those frequencies we all hear differently. It’s crazy easy and fast to do that, and the app will keep your “HearID” curve on file if you want to dabble in other preset curves or dial in your own manually. It really is astonishing how flexible, simple and powerful they’ve made this.  Objectively, these earbuds are fantastic. I’ve used them daily for about 6 months, from my desk to the gym to the woodshop. I’ve listened to hundreds of hours of music and audiobooks. There is absolutely zero distortion, ever. They are loud enough to make me (a drummer and 20year AV pro) happy well below max volume. Bass is tight, clean and loud. Not overly augmented with factory EQ, which some manufacturers use to impress you in the first 10 seconds, but later you realize it’s just a muddy mess below 200Hz. Not here. You’ll be happy even hours later.  Other observations…  Sound Isolation: These do not have active noise cancellation, and that was initially a concern for me as I intended to use them in a woodshop with lots of droning noise...fans, vacuums, motors, saw blades, etc. I wanted to reduce my endofday ear fatigue by reducing the noise level of the shop while also listening to music and books. After using these for 6 months, I no longer want active noise cancellation. I prefer these. They fit tight and do an excellent job of knocking ambient noise down by maybe 20dB or so. Enough to make it easy to hear my audio, but I can still hear the tools as well. Just...not so loud. It’s perfect for me. Likewise, when out for a run, the outside world is quieted, but not muted. I know when a car is coming up behind me, but it’s not distracting.  Fit and Comfort: Anker includes a variety of covers to help make these buds fit snugly. On days when I’ve spent 12+ hours on the woodshop, I have no pain whatsoever from wearing them. It’s easy to forget they’re even there. I do strongly recommend taking the time to try different covers and retainers. The combo I ended up with is different from what I initially thought would work, and I’m glad I took the time to play around with the fit. It went from great to perfect.  Controls: This is another area where Anker went the extra mile. Through the app I was able to set up single, double and longpress for the functions that made sense to me. Very easy, very awesome. The button...thank you Anker for locating the button on the TOP and not the side of the earbuds. It’s an easy button to find and hit, and unlike sidefacing buttons, you don’t end up shoving the bud into your ear canal trying to just press the dang button. Thank you thank you thank you for that.  Wireless Performance: Connection is easy (at least on Android...not sure about iPhone). After the initial pairing, the buds try to start connecting as soon as you pop the case open, so by the time they're in your ears you’re ready to go. If I walk too far from my phone (and it has to be pretty far...the range on these is really good), they reconnect very fast as soon as I’m back in range, with a pleasant little dading sound to let you know you’re back online. You can also use either left or right bud solo. I don’t think there’s anything left to improve in this area. It just works.  Charging and Storage: Remember when The Matrix came out, and everyone was dying to get one of those Nokia phones with the slip cover thing? That’s what the storage case reminds me of. They could have hinged the case. But no, it slides. It’s just cool. Unnecessary, but cool. The case is very solidly built and feels premium to the touch. And since Anker is also known for their charging and battery products, I guess it’s no surprise that the case will charge the heck out of your buds without being plugged in for...I dunno, a long time. They certainly didn’t skimp on the case battery. When the case does need charging, you have that beautiful USBC jack, OR Qi wireless charging. I usually just toss it on the wireless charger a few times a week whether it's needed or not. In any event, this works out really well for longdistance travel. I recently drove a UHaul 2500 miles over 4 days, and although I didn’t use the earbuds the whole time, I did use them a lot and never had to plug the case in. Niiiiice.  Credit where credit is due, and Anker is a special company. They are highly attentive and their customer service is outstanding. When I first received my Liberty 2 Pros, I noticed that the right earbud didn’t always take a full charge. A quick message to Anker, and they jumped on it immediately and sent me a whole new pair, with their apologies. Not sure what caused the issue...probably a bum battery cell. This happens to everyone from time to time and is unavoidable with small electronics. I’ve installed $70k digital audio consoles with minor issues like that. The difference is how the manufacturer deals with these rare speed bumps. I will continue to buy Anker because I know that even if there is a rare issue like that, they will make it right so fast your head will spin. Today, my family of 6 has a total of 8 different Anker wireless audio products. We all love them and use them constantly. We no longer buy any other brand of charging products either. These guys are killing it. Read more", "First, so you know better what I base my opinion on: I own a few decent audiophile gear, from Sennheiser headphone, B&W headphones, PSB and KEF home theater speakers, B&O iem and some more.  These L2P where recommended multiple times to me in am audiophile forum I follow and were praised for their clarity, deep bass, soundstage and instruments separation. I was not set on it but decided to give it a try as I wanted some good TWS that I could use for both music and also 1 side during job for both some music and phone calls (without losing total environment awareness as with dual iem).  At first, I found those TWS to be WAY too dark and bassy for my taste. I'm somewhat a basshead yet those Soundcore had some much deep and powerful bass I could hardly believe it. It is clearly impressive as the bass has no issue dwelling in the 30hz range and even lower. Heck, they have nothing to envy to my B&W P7 full size headphones! It was almost too much for the basshead in me. Mids and upper were clean and well defined with an Ok soundstage but slightly less wide than the P7.  Since I know how burnin can change the character of speakers, I gave them a nice full charge and let them burn during the night on some deep house at about 70% volume. The next day, I charged them and gave another burnin of about 6hours before charging them again for a real test.  I went and downloaded the app, updated the buds firmware and tried the app hearing test which configure each buds for your hearing. It is a very simple test which plays some frequency at various level and where you indicate if you can still hear it by pressing a button. It starts with the left hear and in the upper frequency (68khz) and gradually lowers into bass territory, before starting over with the right hear.  I can say the results were very impressive! The Soundcore Liberty 2 Pro opened up and became more balanced to my hear. The bass wasn't overpowering anymore but simply present, deep and powerful. The voice where more refined and the high are simply great. ABing them with my home theater, PSB, B&O, B&W and Sennheiser, I quickly became addicted to their signature and sonic capabilities to the point I never use any of anymore (appart from the Sennheiser hardwired to the PC).  Trust me, those are very capable little buds with their dual driver. You'll hear details not present in many other audiophile gear worth multiple time the price of those L2P.  It has now been about 5 months and their are my only daily driver now. Charge last me between 5 to 8 hours depending on the volume I listen to and recharging them is a breeze. The sliding cover on the charging case is very well executed and allows you to pick it up from your pocket and open with with 1 hand. The magnets are strong enough to keep the buds in place and even to drag them in the position they should be if you do put them in without worrying about perfect positioning. The case battery usually last me about 3 days when using the buds 812hours daily (sometimes 1 hear only at job) which is more then enough. I have to worry about my phone not lasting long enough before worrying about the buds ;)  Speaking of case. Getting the buds out of the case will pair them to my android in about 5 seconds. The connection is rock solid and I often use them 50' from my phone without losing on transmission quality or having compression artifact. It does happen once in a while that only 1 of the 2 bud will pair but it is instantly fixed by either rebooting both buds with the control or putting them back in the case and out again. Most of the time it happened, I had 1 bud already out and playing before I toom the other bud from the case to switch from 1 hear listening to both hears.  My downsides are minimal and involve comfort, call quality and some minimal sibilance in a few songs. I do have extremely small hear canals (and also very finicky about comfort) and feel some pressure after listening to them for 23hr+ in a row. Moving to the smallest tip helped but didn't totally negate this. After wearing them a full day, I do feel some relief when removing them but it isn't enough to keep me from using them. As for the sibilance, it isn't present in every song (only hear it once in a while) and I don't notice it anymore unless looking for it specifically, but felt like you might be better knowing about it. None of my coworker heard it, except one who could notice it after I told him to listen specifically for it at a particular timestamp in a song I know to produce it.  Phone call quality is hit or miss depending on how you use the TWS. Using only 1 bud in a noisy environment will leave the bud trying to figure which sound to cut off yet missing the mics from the other bud to help it doing it. The result can sometimes be subpar call quality for the person you speak with. On your side, it'll be excellent no matter what. From your side, the buds are so clear you'll prefer using them than your S20 or whatever highend phone you use. If your interlocutor needs to hear you perfectly, I'd recommend using both buds for phone calls and avoid construction site noise. If you can't avoid strong noise, the galaxy bud + might be a better choice as their call quality is slightly better in noisy environment.  Still, those very small issue aren't enough to keep them from being my favorite. I love them so much that I bought a second pair for home use only. I was so hyped with the Liberty 2 Pro that wanted people to know about it, so I lent my second pair to some coworker for them to test the buds. I can say that 2 out of 3 purchased a pair for themselves in the following month. That goes saying something.  So overall, I fully recommend those bud. The sound quality is second only to the Gemini and maybe the N10 pro, but at a fraction of the price.  Good job Soundcore, I was seriously impressed! Read more", 'Ich hatte mir die Kopfhörer damals nach einem Video auf dem Youtubekanal „Linustechtips“ gekauft. Es waren meine ersten Bluetooth Kopfhörer und ich war entsprechend skeptisch. Der Sound ist für mich ein wahres Highlight. Ich habe einige Zeit mit den verschiedenen EQ Einstellungen in der App herumprobiert, aber in den meisten Fällen nutze ich das Standardprofil. Besonders hervorheben möchte ich noch, dass InEars aufgrund ihrer Bauweise und ihrem Sitz oft keine besonders große Klangbühne abbilden können. Das ist auch bei diesen so. Ich höre sehr gern Hörspiele und Hörbücher und besonders hierbei hilft es ungemein dabei in die Geschichte abzutauchen. Einige Nutzer berichten von einem gewissen Grundrauschen wenn der Hörer aktiviert ist. All Reviews: ['i highly recommend this', 'These earbuds are great for the price of SGD 5x that I got these for. However, the FE buds more than give the CX a run for its money. For everyday general use i think the FE buds are hard to beat for the price I paid.', 'Very good to use and hear. What else is needed.', 'Good deal at $53. Not really an audiophile but sounds good. More or less comparable to high end models. Unfortunately have to pick between ANC or volume controls. All Reviews: ['WH1000XM3を愛用しています。スタイリッシュな見た目に惹かれてこのモデルも購入してみました。やはり、WH1000XM3のほうが音質は良いです。低音が弱く、チャカチャカして聞こえます。ここは好みですが。ノイズキャンセリングについては文句ありません。ただ、アプリのオプティマイザーは使用できないのでその点についても、1000XM3が良いです。 1000XM3は型落ちで値段がほとんど変わりませんから、個人的にはそちらをおすすめします。', '数時間使用することもありますが思ったより、ずっと装着していても疲れません。ある程度のノイズキャンセリング効果があり、屋外からの電車の音などがあまり気にならず音楽に集中することができます。デスクトップPCで使っているのですが 最初のBluetooth接続に10回くらい認識させるのが大変でした。やはりスマホ、WALKMANだとアプリですぐ繋がりやすいようです。', '今まで使ってきたイヤホンヘッドホンの遍歴はVictorのHPRX900→SONYのMDR100A、WIC310→今回のWHH910Nです。  比較の対象がMDR100Aになりますが最初は100Aより全体的に音が曇っているように感じました。 どうもこれがノイズキャンセリングの効果のようで、今までこの機能を使ったことがない人はそう感じると思います。 この無音のフィルターに慣れる前提ではありますが100Aと同じくらいの音質に感じました。 有線接続でも使えますがその場合もヘッドホンの電源はONにしないといけません。 電源を入れていないと素人の自分でも分かるくらい違和感のある音しか出ませんが、電源を入れさえすれば有線でも無線でも音の違いは無いと感じました。 ノイズキャンセリングについては外の音が1/2〜1/3になるといった感じです。 耳を抑えるようにR側(右手側)の側面に触れると流してる音を抑えて外の音を取り込んでくれる機能もあります。 面白い機能ではあるんですが話しかけられた時普通のヘッドホンより相手が何を言っているのか聞き取れなかったり気付かなかったりする場合もありそうだったので使う状況によっては注意が必要かもしれません。  最初に使っていたHPRX900は値段もそこそこで満足出来る音で気に入ってたんですが、長時間の使用すると耳が痛くなったり重さでヘッドホンがズレたりコードで動きが制限されたりと気になる部分は多かったです。 そこからMDR100Aに切り替えた時に使用感がかなり違って音以外の良さを知りました。 暫く100Aを使っていましたがスマートフォンから軒並みイヤホンジャックが消え、仕方なくWIC310を買ったのがBluetoothのWHH910Nを買おうと思う切っ掛けになり、デザインも近いH900Nと迷いましたがバッテリーとBluetoothの規格、それに重さが違うようなのでH910Nを選びました。 長時間つけてても痛くならない疲れない等の負担の少なさを100Aで感じていて、H910Nはその良さを引き継いでくれています。 (ずれにくさについてはイヤーパッドの形やフレームが変わったお陰なのか少し良くなってる?) 100Aで唯一不便だと感じていた有線限定の部分もクリアしている良いヘッドホンです。  色はアッシュグリーンを選びました。 画像は目で見えた色と近くなるように撮影しています。 グリーンといっても案外抑えめの緑で暗い所など場合によっては灰色に見えるかもしれません。 イヤーパッドは少し赤みのある燻んだ肌色で的確にコレ!と言い表せません。 アジャスト部分のパーツは本体の色に近いメタリック、ヘアライン?で仕上げられています。 触った感じはツルツルしたプラスチックや摩擦を感じるシリコンとは少し違う不思議な触り心地です。 Read more', '長く使っていたPlantronicsの安いBluetoothヘッドホンの代わりに買いました。ノイズキャンセルは快適だし他の方も書かれているように装着感は快適です。長時間使っていても耳が痛くなることはありません。 問題はその音質でヘッドホンとしては致命的です。耳栓越しに聴いているようなもやっとした音は5000円のPlantronicsの会議用ヘッドホンのほうが遥かに高音質に感じられるほどです。会話を聞きとりやすいチューニングなのかといえばそういう訳でもなく、ひたすら不明瞭なこもった音。 評価できる点は安定した接続と強力なノイズキャンセル機能のみです。騒音がひどい環境で睡眠をとるには悪くないと思います。音質に関しては1000円のヘッドホンでもこれよりましなものはあると思います。']

Names: JBL JBLE15BLK Harman E15 In-Ear Headphone - Black
About Phone: JBL Signature Sound, 1-button universal remote with microphone, Lightweight and comfortable, Tangle-free fabric cable, Multiple size ear tips
All Reviews: ['Ich habe schon einige InEars mit Freisprechfunktion durchprobiert: Sony MDREX450AP, MDRXB50APB.CE7 oder Philips SHE9005A/00 bzw. SHE9105SL/00 weil ich lange Zeit die SHE9000 oder SHE8xx Serien als Kopfhörer hatte. Auch günstige Anbieter wie CSL 640 Ultimate, aber auch frühere noch hochwertigere InEar von Sony oder sehr gute OverEar von Sennheiser um Tonprobleme beim Videoschnitt zu erkennen.  Was finde ich an diesen so gut, dass ich glatt eine Rezension schreibe?  a) Es gibt viele passende Silikonstücke, die gut halten und gut auswechselbar sind und sehr gut abschließen, d.h. es isoliert das Geräusch *nach* außen und *von* außen, was beides sehr angenehm ist  b) Das Plastik ist leicht, aber hochwertig und wirkt sehr stabil und ist sehr glatt, d.h. man bleibt nicht hängen oder es verfängt sich kein Schmutz darin  c) Das Kabel ist stoffummantelt und ich habe es noch nie geschafft zu verknoten und selbst nach 1 Jahr ist es noch immer hochwertig (siehe Foto)  d) Der Stecker ist gewinkelt, und zwar nicht um 90° sondern um circa 120°  das ist großartig! Warum ist da noch nie jemand draufgekommen?  e) Die Länge des Kabels (1,3 statt 1,2 (zu kurz) oder 1,5 (zu lang) Meter Länge), die Länge des Abschnitts bis zum Stoffkabel und die Höhe des Mikrofons passt ebenfalls perfekt. Auch das obere Kabel ist etwas dicker und dadurch "glatter" als die filigranen Kabel mancher neuerer Marken InEars. Die Taste beim Mikrofon ist für Abheben/Auflegen bzw. Play/Pause und funktioniert mit allen für mich wichtigen Apps (Telefon, Podcast Addict, Google Play Music).  f) Die Geräusche, die das Kabel selbst erzeugt, sind fast Null. Mit manchen der Kopfhörer die ich oben genannt habe bekommt man beim Joggen alle Zustände weil man sich bei diesen Geräuschen die das Rutschen der Kleidung verursacht am liebsten an das Ohr fassen und es abreißen möchte.  g) Die Tonqualität finde ich für Kopfhörer dieser Preisklasse extrem ausgewogen  gerade Sprache ist sehr präsent  wer wie ich extrem viel Podcasts hört und gerne joggt, aber auch Musik hört, für den sind sie m.E. ideal geeignet. Ich finde nicht, dass die Mitten extrem überbetont sind, meines Erachtens kommt alles recht schön heraus und klingt sehr angenehm. Sie sind jedenfalls nicht so basslastig wie manche Modelle von Philips, wo man so "eingelullt" wird, dass man danach dasselbe Musikstück o.ä. ohne die Bassverstärkung nicht mehr hören kann.  h) Qualität. Ich bin schon 12 mal versehentlich draufgestiegen (man erkennt am Foto eine kleine Schramme an der Kante) und sehr oft passiert es mir, dass wenn ich die Schuhe binde oder in Bodennähe arbeite und dann von der Hocke wieder nach oben gehe, dass sich die Schlaufe "unter" mein Knie geschummelt hat und beim Aufstehen "reißt" man sich so richtig schön die Kopfhörer aus dem Ohr. Viele bisherige InEars haben dadurch oft nur 48 Monate lang gelebt und hatten dann am linken oder rechten Ohr Unterbrechungen  eben der klassische Kabelbruch. Bisher ist mir das bei diesen Modellen erspart geblieben  vielleicht bin ich mittlerweile auch etwas vorsichtiger geworden  aber ich bin auch zum ersten mal in meinem Leben richtig zufrieden mit InEars und kann sie vor allem wegen des guten Preis/LeistungsVerhältnisses durchaus empfehlen.  Ich habe mir soeben wieder ein Modell gekauft. Für diese Bewertung wurde ich nicht bezahlt, ich kenne die Firma JBL nicht persönlich und arbeite auch nicht indirekt dafür. Aber vielleicht ist es für jemanden hilfreich für den ähnliche Faktoren ausschlaggebend sind.  PS: BluetoothHeadsets hatte ich schon diverse Modelle probiert und anfangs war ich oft überzeugt, jedoch traten im Zeitverlauf immer wieder Probleme an den Tag  für mich ist jedenfalls wichtig, dass beide Ohren "gecovert" sind da ich vom Telefon zum Audiohören nahtlos wechseln möchte, und bei Business Meetings lege ich das Handy immer auf den Kabelsalat drauf und stelle es auf Lautlos, also so schlimm ist das auch wieder nicht und dafür funktioniert es *immer* und schont den Akku (mein OnePlus6 hält dadurch immer genau 2 Tage durch). Read more', "This headphone is not bad. It has the JBL Signature Sound™. But having used another JBL headphone (the T200A which had the JBL Pure Bass™ sound) before this one, I prefer the former.  I mainly listen to Rock, Metal, Jazz, Blues, etc. In my opinion, headphones with JBL Pure Bass™ are best suited for this type of music.  The E15 is sort of a Generalist Jackofalltrades headphone. It's OK for all types of music similar to the Sennheiser CX 180.  EDIT: I was seriously wrong in my appraisal of this headphone. After using the headphone for more than 6 months and reading more on this topic, I have totally changed my mind. The T series headphones by JBL are actually very bassheavy while the E series has a flat frequency response. So, the former is actually better for Hiphop and EDM, not Rock/Metal. The E series is much better for Rock/Metal/Jazz/Blues.
